<blockquote class="messageText SelectQuoteContainer ugc baseHtml">
<div class="bbCodeBlock bbCodeQuote" data-author="Killer_Whale">
<aside>
<div class="attribution type">Killer_Whale said:
<a href="goto/post?id=5529854#post-5529854" class="AttributionLink">&uarr;</a>
</div>
<blockquote class="quoteContainer"><div class="quote">waste actions reacquiring bonds for what we&#039;ve lost.</div><div class="quoteExpand">Click to expand...</div></blockquote>
</aside>
</div>Eventually, I expect Regina will be spending literally all of her actions manabonding or learning languages while slivers do everything else. A 1% loss rate means we could sustain 300 mana use per turn (without spawning additional queens, of course). 5% means we can sustain 60. Either number is enough to do basically everything you could ever want to do in MTG. I suspect that, when (and if) we start getting that much mana, we will just start pumping it into queenspawns with huge special rates so we can have armies of just special slivers. Either that or we could produce some kind of mana engine technology, though that would require significant research into artifice.<br/>
<br/>
All of this is also ignoring Gemhide Sliver, which makes slivers tap for mana. Get a Gemhide, cluster as many spawned slivers around it as possible (research math for stacking irregular objects <img src="styles/default/xenforo/clear.png" class="mceSmilieSprite mceSmilie62" alt=":lol" title="Laugh    :lol"/>), create super efficient mana dynamo. Also ignores Basal Sliver, which lets us sacrifice slivers for black mana. Each Hive Spawn costs 4N mana and produces at least 8N slivers, which we can sacrifice for 16N mana. Have a bunch of hives working in series and we can get a massive mana engine running at no net food loss, as each spawned sliver can hunt for two units of food the turn they become adults before being sacrificed for mana as a free action at the end of the turn. Research some sort of drain life spell and we can be throwing nukes at our enemies pretty fast. <br/>
<br/>
I took a look, and the best utility sliver we can get with green and white mana is Harmonic Sliver, which destroys artifacts and enchantments. The obvious application of that is to force our enemies to fight us empty-handed, while we still charge into battle with super adorable spine horrors.
<div class="messageTextEndMarker">&nbsp;</div>
</blockquote>
