<div class="messageInfo primaryContent">
<div class="messageContent">
<article>
<blockquote class="messageText SelectQuoteContainer ugc baseHtml">
Today&#039;s extended post brought to you by the power of spending 13 hours in airplanes and airports.<br/>
<hr/> <br/>
<div style="text-align: center"> <br/>
<span style="font-size: 22px">Chapter 4: <a href="https://forums.sufficientvelocity.com/posts/5509740/" class="internalLink">Digging In</a></span>&#8203;</div> <br/>
Regina tailbounced through the woods as fast as she could go, the dragon rumbling along behind her. Even at its slowest speed she still had to move quickly to stay ahead, and it was exhausting. Worse, the stench of it made her want to vomit.<br/>
<br/>
She wasn&#039;t actually slowing it down that much; the dragon was so big that it needed to move slowly among the trees. Still, the distance to the edge of the the area the elves patrolled wasn&#039;t that great. They reached the spot where she&#039;d been warned off within an hour, at which point they stopped so that Gil could tell the dragon to open its mouth (again, why was its mouth where its butt should be?!) and let Regina swarm inside. Gil was driving with the seat raised so that his head stuck out through the dragon&#039;s back. He wore the pendant prominently displayed around his neck.<br/>
<br/>
They went ahead at a slow crawl, stopping periodically to call out. They hadn&#039;t gone more than another five minutes when three elves dropped out of the trees onto the dragon&#039;s back, their arrows aimed at Gil&#039;s head.<br/>
<br/>
&quot;Whoa, whoa!&quot; Gil said. He made the dragon stop and raised his hand. &quot;Look, I&#039;ve got a thing! Alassiel gave it to me! I&#039;m a friend, really!&quot;<br/>
<br/>
The elves looked at one another. Their leader relaxed his bow and reached forward, lifting the pendant from around Gil&#039;s neck and studying it carefully.<br/>
<br/>
&quot;Gi nathlam hí,&quot;{??} the leader said, waving for the others to put their weapons down. &quot;Man le carel sí?&quot;<br/>
<br/>
&quot;Yeah, gee nat lam to you too,&quot; Gil said. &quot;Okay, first thing: I&#039;ve got a friend with me.&quot; He made a calming gesture to the elves, then reached down to flip the switch that made the dragon open its mouth. The beast&#039;s jaw started winding down with a loud whirring sound as Gil pulled himself up out of the driver&#039;s seat and slid down the side of the dragon. He moved to the creature&#039;s flank before saying, &quot;Okay, Regina. Come on out.&quot;<br/>
<br/>
Regina slithered out from the dragon&#039;s belly slowly, keeping her arms down and doing everything she could to appear non-hostile. Given that she was the size of a small horse, covered in bladed spikes, and had a pair of scythes instead of hands...well, it wasn&#039;t the most successful effort.<br/>
<br/>
The elves raised their bows in a flash.<br/>
<br/>
&quot;Whoa, whoa!&quot; Gil said, stepping in front of Regina and patting the air with both hands in a &#039;calm down&#039; gesture. &quot;She&#039;s a friend. Yeah, she looks like a nightmare but she&#039;s fine really. She even likes to cuddle, which is a real adventure but it&#039;s still kinda sweet. Easy! Friend!&quot;{stop ?? hive-mate ???? hive-mate}<br/>
<br/>
The elf leader looked at Regina, then looked at Gil with an &#039;are you crazy?&#039; expression.<br/>
<br/>
&quot;Mellon?&quot; he asked.<br/>
<br/>
&quot;Yeah, yeah,&quot; Gil said. &quot;Melon. Whatever, sure, let&#039;s have fruit. Just don&#039;t shoot her.&quot;{??}<br/>
<br/>
The elves paused, then slowly relaxed their bows. They didn&#039;t put them away, though.<br/>
<br/>
&quot;Good, great. We&#039;re all friends here. Nice big bunch of friends,&quot; Gil said. &quot;FYI for you guys, we&#039;re pretty sure there&#039;s a whole bunch of ogres coming this way pretty soon. We thought you might like a heads-up.&quot;{??}<br/>
<br/>
The elf frowned and glanced at his second, who shrugged helplessly.<br/>
<br/>
&quot;Look, I&#039;m Gil,&quot; Gil said pointing to himself. &quot;Gil Macdonald.&quot;<br/>
<br/>
The leader nodded. Pointing to himself and the others in turn he said, &quot;Thalaweston. Aparchel. Alwephen.&quot;<br/>
<br/>
&quot;Okay, good,&quot; Gil said. &quot;Thalaweston, elf. Aparchel, elf. Alwephen, elf. Gil, human. Savvy?&quot;<br/>
<br/>
The leader stared at him a moment until understanding dawned. He pointed to each of the four in turn. &quot;Elf, elf, elf, human. Savvy.&quot;<br/>
<br/>
&quot;Okay, good,&quot; Gil said. &quot;Human, elf. Ogre.&quot; He raised his hands over his head to indicate height, then put them out to indicate bulk. Finally he stuck two fingers to his lower jaw, pointing up to emulate tusks. &quot;Waaagh!&quot; He looked at the leader carefully. &quot;Ogre. Savvy?&quot;<br/>
<br/>
The leader laughed a clear, bell-like laugh. &quot;Ogre, savvy. Elf, human, ogre. Savvy.&quot;<br/>
<br/>
&quot;Good. Okay. Lots of ogres&quot;--Gil pointed off into the woods with a broad sweeping gesture--&quot;ogre, ogre, ogre, ogre, ogre. Ogres come here.&quot; He pointed down with both hands.<br/>
<br/>
The leader rolled his eyes. &quot;Ogres come here,&quot; he said, in a tone that clearly appended a &#039;Well, duh!&#039; to the end.<br/>
<br/>
Gil sighed. &quot;Okay, fine. Look, me and Regina want to hole up with you guys. That work?&quot;{??}<br/>
<br/>
The patrol leader frowned and cocked his head.<br/>
<br/>
&quot;Gil, Regina, you&quot;--he pointed at the elven group--&quot;go elf home?&quot; Gil said, pointing into the woods.<br/>
<br/>
The leader shook his head. He pointed at Gil, then pointed deeper into the woods. &quot;Gil, gi nathlam hí.&quot;{??} He pointed at the dragon, then at Regina, and said, &quot;Ego.&quot;{??}<br/>
<br/>
&quot;Oh, come on,&quot; Gil said in exasperation. &quot;She&#039;s killed ogres too.&quot;{??}<br/>
<br/>
The elf leader shook his head.<br/>
<br/>
&quot;Goddamnit,&quot; Gil grumbled. He sighed. &quot;Fine. Gil, Regina, stay here. Build home. Savvy?&quot;{Gil, Regina, dig hive}<br/>
<br/>
There was no way the elf was going to get that on the first try, so Regina started digging to make the point.<br/>
<br/>
The elf leader watched her with a frown.<br/>
<br/>
&quot;Regina dig,&quot; Gil said making swimming motions with his hands. &quot;Big hole. Gil, Regina, live in hole.&quot; He pointed to himself, then jabbed his finger at the ground a few times.<br/>
<br/>
The elf looked at him in confusion, then shrugged. He bent and drew a line in the dirt. He gestured to the ground beyond the line, where Regina was busy digging. &quot;Dâf ,&quot; he said. He pointed to the other side of the line, deeper into elf territory. &quot;Gil: Gi nathlam hí,&quot; he said with an exaggerated nod. He pointed at the dragon and then at Regina, then back towards elven territory. &quot;Daro,&quot; he said, shaking his head. He pulled his sword an inch out of the sheath to make the point.<br/>
<br/>
&quot;And a very fine screw you to you as well, you blond asshole,&quot;{??} Gil said with a friendly smile. &quot;I hope your prissy elvish balls get cancer.&quot;{??} He gave a friendly wave, and nodded his understanding of the rules.<br/>
<br/>
The patrol leader gave him a polite nod in return and a small smile. The elf watched for a moment longer, then vanished into the woods with his companions in tow.<br/>
<br/>
<br/>
<div style="text-align: center">o-o-o-o&#8203;</div> <br/>
Once they knew that the &#039;hide with the elves&#039; plan was out, Gil and Regina had a very long and comical discussion about what to do. Empassioned pidgin and wild gestures flew back and forth. Gil was of the opinion that it was time to &quot;get the hell outta Dodge&quot;. He&#039;d only been staying in hopes that perhaps the shift would reverse itself and he&#039;d find himself home again...or, failing that, that maybe some of his fellow warriors might have shifted through with him and would come looking at his last known position.<br/>
<br/>
Regina, on the other hand, wasn&#039;t willing to leave. This area was overhunted--almost certainly by the ogres--but it was rich, and the elves had the potential to be good neighbors and trading partners if a little trust could be built. In particular, the elf bread was a nearly perfect food: massive amounts of energy in a tiny, lightweight package. Finally, she&#039;d scouted this area pretty thoroughly before they approached the elves, and there were a large number of mana wells in the area that she could bond. With a little elbow grease and a moderate amount of ogre-murder this area could be an excellent hive ground, and there was no guarantee that anywhere else would be better. Eventually she had argued Gil around, and convinced him that they should go to the elves.<br/>
<br/>
And then, of course, the elves shut the door in their face. Ah well, they&#039;d just have to dig a door of their own. That was the sliver way, after all.<br/>
<br/>
The place where they set up the hive wasn&#039;t an ideal spot for a hive, but it wasn&#039;t bad either. They were nearly at the top of a shallow hill, so the water table was nice and far down. The woods were relatively thin and the trees that were in the immediate area were small and young. Judging by the smell of the soil there had been a burn here some time ago and the vegetation was still growing back. In a few months, once she had her full growth, Regina would have no problem chopping down these little saplings in order to give a nice wide killing field. In the meantime, what they had would do.<br/>
<br/>
She dug straight into the side of the hill to start, millenia of racial instincts whispering how to shape the walls so they wouldn&#039;t collapse. She made the initial entrance narrow but tall so that Gil could sit up in it to man the largest of his tube weapons, the &#039;.50 cal&#039;. An elevated cubby in the wall gave a place to stash it where it could be accessed quickly but wouldn&#039;t be in the way. For now, though, it was set up outside the hive, just to the side of the entrance.<br/>
<br/>
There wasn&#039;t time for anything fancy, so she simply dug a large hole at the bottom of the shaft, making sure to leave extra space on the edge for Gil because he was a selfish wuss who wouldn&#039;t sleep in a proper cuddlepile just because he got a little stabbed once or twice. Well, maybe three times.<br/>
<br/>
Doing all the work herself was annoying; she had to dig a bit, then drag the dirt up and out before she could dig more. Fortunately, Gil caught on to what was needed. He used Pomorski&#039;s old backpack to haul the dirt out so that she could focus on digging. Things went faster after that.<br/>
<br/>
She would have just hurled the dirt out the entrance and gone back down to dig more. Gil, on the other hand, built it up into a berm a meter and a half high around the hive&#039;s entrance. The only problem was that he&#039;d left a meter-wide gap on the downhill side. Sure, it allowed runoff to flow out and thereby kept the place from flooding, but Gil had put the opening exactly where enemies were most likely to be coming from, and directly in line with the entrance. He&#039;d built a lovely defense and then utterly ruined it, the idiot.<br/>
<br/>
She found herself taking back the unkind thoughts when he had her dig a pit right in the middle of the gap. She took that up a notch to &#039;offering mental apologies&#039; when he jammed stakes into the bottom of the pit and covered it over. Then he took her outside the berm and showed her the two small boxes--&#039;claymores&#039;--that he&#039;d embedded in the dirt, and the carefully-buried green wires that led from them back to the inside of the berm. He went to great lengths to explain their operation to her, repeating it multiple times until he was absolutely certain she understood. Honestly, she was a little offended; how hard did he think it was to understand &#039;don&#039;t stand there or you&#039;ll be killed&#039;? And, to be honest, the &#039;do not touch, ever&#039; part was a little rude but probably wise. She&#039;d leave it for him.<br/>
<br/>
They got the chance to test the defenses a lot sooner than she would have preferred when the ogres came calling. This was no mere patrol group like they&#039;d met before; this was a group of raiders, forty or fifty strong.<br/>
<br/>
Gil was outside the wall, peeing against a tree a few dozen meters from the hive entrance when the ogres&#039; warcries split the late afternoon air. The soldier&#039;s head snapped up and seconds later he was racing up the hill, the ogres twenty meters behind him and gaining fast.<br/>
<br/>
Regina was in the bottom of the hive digging a bit more space; she was still growing fast, and needed to expand the hive every day to prevent Gil from getting accidentally squashed at night. When she heard him yelling her name over the warcries of ogres she came boiling up out of the hive. A quick glance showed her what was needed and she tailbounced over the berm and down the hill as fast as she could go.<br/>
<br/>
The ogres were right on Gil&#039;s heels; he was running flat out, but the creatures were simply faster than a human. He&#039;d drawn his pistol to fire some wild, unaimed shots over his shoulder in hopes of discouraging pursuit but, unfortunately, the ogres were too bloody stupid to be discouraged.<br/>
<br/>
One of the ogres hurled its warclub at Gil&#039;s legs, sending him sprawling. He landed badly, coming down on one hand; he screamed as his wrist snapped, but he kept his head, rolled onto his back, and shot the nearest ogre in the face before it could swing its club. The greenskin&#039;s brains exploded out the back of its head and its dead body fell across Gil&#039;s belly and legs. The air went out of him in a woosh and he involuntarily dropped the pistol.<br/>
<br/>
The ogres howled and pounced, but they had barely a moment to put the boot in on Gil before Regina slammed into them like a boulder, smashing them aside with broad swipes of her claws. She jumped right over Gil to bowl the next two ogres off their feet, taking care to rake her ventral spines across one of them hard enough to virtually split him in half.<br/>
<br/>
Gil managed to push the corpse off of him, get to his feet, and run for the hive. Regina was too fully committed to her charge to turn back easily, so she just kept going, barreling right through the center of the group.<br/>
<br/>
That turned out to be a bad plan. Her scales had grown tough enough to turn aside most greenskin hits, but there were a lot of hits. Worse, the stupid greenskins just <i>would not</i> run, even though they should have seen they were totally overmatched. Instead they pressed in closer, hemming her in and blocking her progress with outthrust clubs and spears whenever she tried to escape. She spun and snapped, trying to smash her way out, but the bodies pressed in tighter and tighter around her. She gutted every ogre that came in reach, but every time she turned to get one, two more would smash her with their clubs from behind.<br/>
<br/>
&quot;Regina, GET DOWN!&quot; Gil bellowed. She dropped flat without a moment&#039;s hesitation.<br/>
<br/>
The world tore apart as Gil cut loose with the .50 cal. With a broken left wrist he was having to pin it down with one leg while traversing with his working right hand. His control wasn&#039;t great, but he was careful on the trigger. The heavy bullets cracked past just overhead, smashing greenskin bodies left and right as Regina did everything she could to crawl into the ground.<br/>
<br/>
The noise, the unfamiliarity, and the fact that they were being slaughtered in job lots were finally enough to make the greenskins break. They didn&#039;t even bother picking up their dead, they just ran. Gil let them go, conserving ammo carefully for what both he and Regina knew would be another raid in the future.<br/>
<br/>
Regina dragged herself to her tails and slithered over to Gil. &quot;High one,&quot; she said, holding up a clawblade.<br/>
<br/>
Gil gave what would have been a chuckle if it weren&#039;t buried under exhaustion, terror, and pain. &quot;High one,&quot; he said, tapping a finger carefully against the flat of her clawblade. &quot;You okay?&quot;<br/>
<br/>
&quot;I&#039;ll live,&quot; she said. &quot;Ow.&quot;<br/>
<br/>
Gil nodded. &quot;Preach it, sister. C&#039;mon, I&#039;ll get the medkit.&quot;<br/>
<br/>
<span style="color: #ccc254">+16s<br/>
+4 food [disgusting but edible something-jerky looted from corpses]<br/>
Ogre bodies are edible, but cannot currently be preserved and therefore do not count towards food needs.<br/>
</span><br/>
<div style="text-align: center">o-o-o-o&#8203;</div> <br/>
For the next few weeks they fortified the hive. Gil parked the dragon--Lobo--just downhill and to the side from the hive, where it would be easy to flee to if they needed to &#039;bug out&#039;. (Regina was a little unclear why Gil always made the happy curving-mouth gesture when he said &#039;bug out&#039; around her.) Between the .50 cal, the claymores, the the wall, the pit trap, and the fact that fighting a sliver queen in the close quarters of her own tunnel was never a good plan...well, the new hive wasn&#039;t impregnable, but it was better than anything else they had. At least, it was until the ammo ran out.<br/>
<br/>
Periodically, Regina would take a break and slither a couple miles to the east. She&#039;d found a free mana well there and she wanted that power; with it, her new hive would be able to spawn some sweet, beautiful children who would be the delight of her life and also fanged engines of ogre destruction.<br/>
<br/>
She was shorting herself on sleep to get everything done in time; she didn&#039;t know how long they had before the ogres showed up in force, but she suspected it wasn&#039;t long. Despite doing the ritual as fast as she could it still took over two weeks to finally bond the well, but when it was done she slithered home in tired satisfaction.<br/>
<br/>
Gil was sitting on the earthen berm with a whittling stakes from a small sapling he&#039;d chopped down with an axe. His arm was still in a sling and his leg was burned from where he&#039;d pressed the .50 cal down with it. He moved slowly and painfully, but he&#039;d proven very ingenious about getting things done with only one working hand. He looked up when she slithered close and sat down in front of him.<br/>
<br/>
&quot;Catch anything?&quot;{hunt successful?} he asked.<br/>
<br/>
She shook her head; she hadn&#039;t been hunting, but she didn&#039;t know how to explain that. Besides, there was something more important to discuss.<br/>
<br/>
&quot;Gil, listen important,&quot; she said. &quot;Important. Regina take many small Regina.&quot;<br/>
<br/>
Gil frowned. &quot;What?&quot;<br/>
<br/>
Regina reached down and scratched a small picture of herself and Gil in the dirt. &quot;Regina. Gil.&quot; She scratched three more pictures of herself, each about a third the size. &quot;Regina take small Regina. And small Regina. And small Regina. Come tonight.&quot;<br/>
<br/>
Gil blinked. &quot;You&#039;re <i>pregnant?</i>&quot;{spawning time now?} he said. She nodded, and he burst out laughing. &quot;Well, don&#039;t look at me--I didn&#039;t do it!&quot;{???}<br/>
<br/>
She shook her head in the gesture she&#039;d learned from him. &quot;Tonight Regina take many small Regina. Safe. Small Regina help Gil, help Regina.&quot;<br/>
<br/>
&quot;Yeah, gotta say: I&#039;m all for mom and apple pie, but this is about the crappiest time imaginable to suddenly be weighed down with kids,&quot;{??} Gil said. &quot;And it&#039;s happening tonight? You couldn&#039;t have told me sooner?&quot;{??}<br/>
<br/>
&quot;Tonight,&quot; Regina said. &quot;Regina take many small Regina. Small Regina help. Small Regina safe. Gil safe with small Regina.&quot;<br/>
<br/>
Gil snorted in amusement. &quot;Yeah, I think I&#039;ll be able to handle myself around a few babies,&quot;{??} he said. A thought suddenly struck him. &quot;Hang on. How many babies?&quot;{query spawn size?}<br/>
<br/>
&quot;Eight,&quot; she said firmly. She&#039;d thought long and hard about that. It was a small hatching, but it would make a good compromise between extra mouths to feed and strength of the hive.<br/>
<br/>
&quot;Eight, huh? Man, I thought my parents had their hands full with two,&quot;{??} Gil said. &quot;Okay, well, I guess we&#039;ll manage. Do they grow as fast as you?&quot;{??}<br/>
<br/>
She cocked her head in confusion.<br/>
<br/>
&quot;Right,&quot; Gil said. He squatted down and tapped a finger on one of the small drawings. &quot;Baby,&quot; he said.<br/>
<br/>
&quot;Baby,&quot; she repeated.<br/>
<br/>
&quot;Baby today,&quot; he said, tapping the sketch again. He drew a line from the sketch to the right, stretching it out a few dozen centimeters, then drew a full-size picture of Regina. &quot;Baby all grown. One year? Two year?&quot;<br/>
<br/>
&quot;Three ten day,&quot; she said. &quot;Not Regina-large. One-half Gil-large, maybe.&quot;<br/>
<br/>
&quot;A <i>month?!</i>&quot; he said. &quot;It&#039;ll be half my size in a <i>month?</i>&quot;{grow quick} He ran a hand through his hair, staring at the sketch in disbelief. &quot;Jesus. Okay, well, that&#039;ll be fun. Can&#039;t imagine how you&#039;re going to make that much milk. Let them eat elf cake, I hope.&quot;{??}<br/>
<br/>
&quot;Regina take little Regina now,&quot; she said. &quot;Gil come?&quot;<br/>
<br/>
&quot;Now like right now?&quot; Gil said. He rubbed his head again. &quot;Christ. Okay, don&#039;t take this wrong, but I&#039;d rather not be in a small, dark, underground space with you while you&#039;re thrashing around in childbirth, Your Pointyness. I&#039;ll keep watch.&quot;{???? Gil not come}<br/>
<br/>
She nodded. &quot;Okay. See you soon.&quot; She turned and slithered into the hive.<br/>
<br/>
Spawning was as painful and as glorious as her mother had promised. Hive spawning wasn&#039;t the joyous release of natural spawning; there was nothing of her body involved. Instead, she drew in the mana from all her bonds and fed it into the runework that she&#039;d embedded in every inch of the hive&#039;s inner surface. The power burned through her like a river of molten light, stinging and sweet all at once. The runes glowed brightly, driving out the darkness that Gil so hated as tendrils of fire and hope danced across the floor and walls. Slowly, oh so slowly, those tendrils curled around themselves and knotted, growing steadily larger as she spun more power into the threads. She only permitted eight of the knots to grow; when more tried to form she brushed them aside, forcing them to straighten out.<br/>
<br/>
She kept the ritual going for hours as the knots grew larger and large before finally congealing and darkening into leathery yellow eggs the size of Gil&#039;s fist. The light of the ritual faded to a starlight glimmer as the spell ended. Moments later, the eggs broke open and eight tiny slivers fell out, creeling with hunger. Regina scooped them in close, delighted with the softness of their scales and the delicious tickling of their not-yet-sharp jaws as they gnawed futiley on her armored legs. She offered each of them a small bit of one of the lembas wafers that Alassiel had given them; each one snatched the morsel in its jaws and rolled on its back, legs kicking in an instinctive disemboweling stroke. Despite the curious lack of response from the very strange &#039;prey&#039;, the newborn sliverlings wolfed the lembas down and cried for more.<br/>
<br/>
Regina obliged, feeding them more until their bellies were so stuffed that she could see individual crumbs of bread against the inside of their skin. The moment they were satiated, the sliverlings were asleep. Regina cuddled them close and followed them into dreams; the birthing process had been exhausting for mother as well as children.<br/>
<br/>
This was the beginning, she thought as she drifted off. Let her and her children get a foothold here and the ogres would regret they&#039;d made an enemy of sliverkind.<br/>
<hr/><span style="color: #c45e3b"> <b>Summary</b></span><br/>
<ul>
<li>Hunting: --</li>
<li>Hunting Cap: --</li>
<li>Food found: +4</li>
<li>Food consumed: 14</li>
<li>Food stores: 41</li>
<li>Money received: +16s</li>
<li>Hive #1 built, with Minimal defenses. Gil&#039;s weapons raise them to Superb.</li>
<li>Born: 8 generic slivers</li>
<li>Regina is: 4/4</li>
</ul><span style="color: #c45e3b">Defense levels are:</span><br/>
<ul>
<li>+18 Gratuitous</li>
<li>+17 Insane</li>
<li>+16 Ridiculous</li>
<li>+15 Crazy</li>
<li>+14 Excessive</li>
<li>+13 Legendary</li>
