<h3 class="userText">
<a href="members/pahan.760/" class="username" dir="auto" itemprop="name">Pahan</a>
 
</h3>
<span class="arrow"><span></span></span>
</div>
</div>
<div class="messageInfo primaryContent">
<div class="messageContent">
<article>
<blockquote class="messageText SelectQuoteContainer ugc baseHtml">
<div class="bbCodeBlock bbCodeQuote" data-author="Killer_Whale">
<aside>
<div class="attribution type">Killer_Whale said:
<a href="goto/post?id=5531274#post-5531274" class="AttributionLink">&uarr;</a>
</div>
<blockquote class="quoteContainer"><div class="quote">Research: Learn fire from Gil, we need this to permanently deal with the Ork spores. And it helps towards food preservation later. (Queen)</div><div class="quoteExpand">Click to expand...</div></blockquote>
</aside>
</div>How urgent is this?<br/>
<br/>
From the IC perspective, I don&#039;t think Regina has any idea about Ork spores. Frankly, we should just devour the bodies of any we kill. The fact that we aren&#039;t humanoid works in our favor here: it doesn&#039;t <i>look</i> like cannibalism.<br/>
<br/>
From the OOC perspective, we might not want to, either, if the Ork reproduction is as described in <a href="http://warhammer40k.wikia.com/wiki/Orks#Reproduction" target="_blank" class="externalLink" rel="nofollow">the wikia page</a>: &quot;Orks release fungal spores, which grow into a plant-like womb underground that nourishes the bodies of the various Orkoid species. This is the entire basis of the Orkoid ecosystem, producing first Squigs, then Snotlings who cultivate the Squigs and the fungus they feed on, then Gretchin to build the Greenskin settlements, and finally the Orks themselves.&quot;<br/>
<br/>
In other words, the spore converts soil nutrients to tasty meat (Squigs), then laborers (Snotlings), and only then anything even remotely dangerous (Gretchin), and is apparently able to do even where normal vegetation can&#039;t survive. So, my sense is that we don&#039;t actually want to destroy the &quot;wombs&quot;, we want to cull them so that they never graduate to Gretchin.<br/>
<br/>
Though, we don&#039;t know how long the lifecycle of a spore is.
<div class="messageTextEndMarker">&nbsp;</div>
</blockquote>
</article>
</div>
